Summary

Based off of the summary of the data, most of the data seems to be unproblematic. However, there is only one observation in the data set that has level 4 for weather (Heavy Rain + Ice Pallets + Thunderstorm + Mist, Snow + Fog), and this might make it hard to make a model that to accurately predict observations for this type of weather due to the lack of data for it.

Histograms

require(ggplot2)  # use the ggplot2 package to create plots
## Loading required package: ggplot2
require(tidyr)  # use tidyr package
## Loading required package: tidyr
# create a new dataframe where registered and casual counts
# are in the same variable, called `count`, and the variable
# `rider` either 'registered' or 'casual', depending on which
# of the original vectors it came from
dataStacked = gather(data, "rider", "count", casual, registered)

# create a histogram object for further use
registered_and_casual = ggplot(dataStacked) + geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = count, 
    y = ..density.., color = rider, fill = rider), position = "identity", 
    alpha = 0.3, binwidth = 30) + labs(title = "Histograms of registered and casual rider counts each day", 
    x = "Count of Bike Users", y = "Density") + theme_bw()

# create plots for each respective categorical variable in
# the data
registered_and_casual + facet_grid(~season) + labs(subtitle = "For each level of season")
registered_and_casual + facet_grid(~holiday) + labs(subtitle = "For each level of holiday")
registered_and_casual + facet_grid(~workingday) + labs(subtitle = "For each level of workingday")
registered_and_casual + facet_grid(~weather) + labs(subtitle = "For each level of weather")

The histograms for the season variable show that the registered rider counts generally show no change (proportion-wise) between seasons, most likely due to the fact that they are regular users of the service and use the bikes for commuting. However, we see that there are a lesser proportion of high counts of casual riders in the spring and the winter, with the spring having the least proportion.

The histograms for the holiday variable appear to show that are a slightly higher proportion of casual rider counts on holidays than on non-holidays; the registered proportions do not seem to show any significant change.

The histograms for the workingday variable show that on working days, there is a lesser proportion of casual rider counts counts and a higher proportion registered counts. This is probably because there would be less casual riders on working days and more registered riders who use the bikes for commuting purposes.

The weather variable shows that the proportions do no not change much between clear/partly cloudy and misty days, meanwhile on light rain/snow days, the there are a higher proportion of lower counts. The heavy rain/snow level, since it only contains one observation, it is surprising to see that there were roughly 125 registered riders but 0 casual riders using the service in that hour time interval.

Pairs plot

# create a pairs plot
require(GGally)  # use GGally for coherent graphics throughout the project
## Loading required package: GGally
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'GGally':
##   method from   
##   +.gg   ggplot2
ggpairs(data[, 6:12], progress = F, title = "Pairs plot for continuous variables")

From the pairs plot, many of the explanatory variables have little to moderate correlation with each other with the exception of the temp and atemp relationship, which is extremely high and is expected due to their nature of being measures of the temperature. We also see that on the plots where casual and registered are the response variables, that their graphs seem to change in the same general fashion. When temperature is low, casual and registered are low; when humidity is very high, the counts seem to plummet; when windspeed is high, the counts are low. From the hour24 plots, its nice to note that the temp and atemp graphs assume sinuous characteristics, and that around 5-10 am and 15-17, registered counts peak and for the casual counts, they peak around noon.

The blob of points on the temp/atemp plot is extremely interesting because they deviate from the main trend and create their own group. Analyzing this blob with a summary might give more insight. In addition, having 0 humidity seems to be abnormal, so analyzing data summary corresponding to that is important. Analyzing 0 windspeed might show something significant, that will be done too.

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Generally, the counts of riders increase per year and follow a sinuous pattern, where the beginning of a year has less riders, the riders peak around fall, then they level down a little. Because of this sinuous patter, season and yr seem to have a big effect on the counts of the riders. However, we can see that the counts for casual riders vary little between year and do not peak that high in comparison to its local minimums.

Heatmap

# start to construct a heat map with annotation and scaling
require(pheatmap)
## Loading required package: pheatmap
# create colors
seqPal <- colorRampPalette(c("orange", "black", "blue"))(50)
seqPal <- (c("yellow", "gold2", seqPal))
seqPal <- rev(seqPal)
colSeason <- c("Blue", "Green", "Red", "Black")
names(colSeason) <- c("winter", "spring", "summer", "fall")
colHoliday = c("red", "green")
names(colHoliday) = c("No", "Yes")
colWorkingDay = c("red", "green")
names(colWorkingDay) = c("No", "Yes")
colWeather = c("Blue", "Green", "Red", "Black")
names(colWeather) = c(levels(data$weather))

# scale data
dataScaled = data.frame(apply(data[, sapply(data, function(x) is.numeric(x))], 
    2, scale))
# data frame for categorical data
dataCat = data[, !sapply(data, function(x) is.numeric(x))]
row.names(dataScaled) = row.names(data)
# find breakpoints and only for the 90% data in middle
qnt = quantile(as.numeric(data.matrix((dataScaled))), probs = c(0.05, 
    0.95))
breakpoints = seq(qnt[1], qnt[2], length = length(seqPal) + 1)
# create heatmap
pheatmap(dataScaled, col = seqPal, scale = "column", breaks = breakpoints, 
    annotation_row = dataCat[, c(-1, -6)], annotation_colors = list(holiday = colHoliday, 
        workingday = colWorkingDay, weather = colWeather, season = colSeason))

The heatmap also shows some how the variables interact with each other. Besides the obvious correlations (atemp and temp or registered and casual or season and temp/atemp), we can see some previous things that were noticed on the histograms, casual and registered roughly change according to workingday as well as weather. Other than those, it is hard to clearly tell further things from the heatmap.

3: Regression Analysis

Note : For the following sections, I will be removing several observations that were noted in the previous Pairs plot section to inconsistent with the rest of the data and these were most likely due to errors in data collecting instruments.

Also, the datetime variable will not be used and yr and hour24 will be used in place of it; weekday was also only created for EDA purposes to differentiate between days, but it will not be used for this section.

# exclude observations from data set
data = data[!(data$temp > 20 & data$atemp < 15), ]
data = data[!(data$humidity == 0), ]

Casual Variable

First, I will do regression on the casual variable.

The first regression that will be attempted is finding a simple model with no interactions just to get a base in seeing how the model would be like.

# first casual fit with nothing
casual.fit1 = lm(casual ~ ., data = data[, c(-1, -14, -11)])

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(casual.fit1)
## Warning: not plotting observations with leverage one:
##   5610

## Warning: not plotting observations with leverage one:
##   5610

Based on the plots, it it’s clear that the right side of the fitted values do not follow the normal curve, so a tranformation can easily fix this (to an extent), and we can also observe its effect on the residual vs fitted plot. Specifically, log(casual + 1) will be used. Because some of the observations have 0 count, +1 is neccessary to allow the log function to map the value. log is used because there are many values that deviate from the normal curve, and it should be able to bring most of the observations to proximity to the normal curve.

# second casual fit with transformation
casual.fit2 = lm(log(casual + 1) ~ ., data = data[, c(-1, -14, 
    -11)])

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(casual.fit2)
## Warning: not plotting observations with leverage one:
##   5610

## Warning: not plotting observations with leverage one:
##   5610

The transformation makes it clear that there are several observations which create a regular pattern in the residual vs fitted plots. Based on what we see in these plots, it might be reasonable to say that the residuals vs fitted plots are composed of a multitude of these patterns and probably caused by some aspect that the data is composed of observations over time.

The second regression that will be attempted is using all the variables and their interaction with the categorical variables, this is because at first glance, the categorical variables seem to have a major effect on the distributions of responses, so using the interactions might give a good model. The only exception is that yr appears to only affect the counts by a static amount, so I will leave that variable without any interactions.

# third casual fit with interactions
casual.fit3 = lm(log(casual + 1) ~ (. - season - workingday - 
    holiday - weather - yr) * (season * holiday * workingday * 
    weather) + yr, data = data[, c(-1, -14, -11)])

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(casual.fit3)
## Warning: not plotting observations with leverage one:
##   392, 393, 394, 395, 396, 3686, 3696, 3697, 3700, 5782, 9657, 9658, 9662, 9664, 10214

## Warning: not plotting observations with leverage one:
##   392, 393, 394, 395, 396, 3686, 3696, 3697, 3700, 5782, 9657, 9658, 9662, 9664, 10214
## Warning in sqrt(crit * p * (1 - hh)/hh): NaNs produced

## Warning in sqrt(crit * p * (1 - hh)/hh): NaNs produced

There is not much change in the residuals graph compared to the previous model, however the residuals vs leverage graph has changed considerably; more observations are being given more leverage. Next, I’ll try interactions somewhat based on the clustering in the heatmap and the patterns seen in the histograms that were constructed.

# fourth casual fit wtih more interactions
casual.fit4 = lm(log(casual + 1) ~ ((temp + atemp) * yr * season) * 
    (windspeed + hour24) * humidity * weather + workingday + 
    holiday, data = data[, c(-1, -14, -11)])

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(casual.fit4)
## Warning: not plotting observations with leverage one:
##   5610

## Warning: not plotting observations with leverage one:
##   5610
## Warning in sqrt(crit * p * (1 - hh)/hh): NaNs produced

## Warning in sqrt(crit * p * (1 - hh)/hh): NaNs produced

It appears that nothing much changes even with the changes that I make to the interactions, so I will use the second model that I fitted with a transformation for my final model. I considered using \(R^{2}\) as a measure of how well a model fitted, however, it would naturally increase with more interactions because more variables are added into the model. In addition, this model had less leverage for the points, it would seem better to use this since the residuals vs fitted had the same shape as the other models with interactions added. I am not using the very first model due to the extreme deviation from the normal curve as shown in its normal q-q plot. The few outliers that are flagged will also be removed from the data since it looks like they deviate from the bulk of the data.

# create final casual fit with outliers omitted
casual.final = lm(log(casual + 1) ~ ., data = data[!(rownames(data) %in% 
    c("10262", "7148", "5804")), c(-1, -14, -11)])

Registered Variable

Now, I will perform regression with the registered variable as the response variable and follow the same patterns as the previous regressions I did with casual. I suspect that the response will again need a transformation, so I apply it for the first model that I fit.

# first registered fit with no interactions, but with
# transformation
registered.fit1 = lm(log(registered + 1) ~ ., data = data[, c(-1, 
    -10, -14)])

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(registered.fit1)
## Warning: not plotting observations with leverage one:
##   5610

## Warning: not plotting observations with leverage one:
##   5610

It appears that the similar results are obtained compared to regression with the casual variable, however, the same check mark pattern in the casual regressions does not seem to be present in the registered variable. I’ll see if I can improve my fit by using the same interactions as my regressions with the casual variable.

# second registered fit with interactions
registered.fit2 = lm(log(registered + 1) ~ (. - season - workingday - 
    holiday - weather - yr) * (season * holiday * workingday * 
    weather) + yr, data = data[, c(-1, -14, -10)])

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(registered.fit2)
## Warning: not plotting observations with leverage one:

It seems that the fit has somewhat worsened; the Normal Q-Q shows that the average of the residuals seem to deviate more from the normal curve, and the leverage for many points has increased. This fit has also created observations with 1 leverage, so it seems that I’ll continue to try the same type of model that I fitted for casual.

# third registered fit with more interactions
registered.fit3 = lm(log(registered + 1) ~ ((temp + atemp) * 
    yr * season) * (windspeed + hour24) * humidity * weather + 
    workingday + holiday, data = data[, c(-1, -14, -10)])

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(registered.fit3)

The fit is similar the previous one, however the leverages have increased more (but there seems to have been no leverage one observations because R didn’t prompt it). Because I observe similar patterns in the graphs as with the casual regressions, I’ll be using the same reasoning as with the casual final model to use the first model that I fitted and without the flagged outliers as my final model.

# create final registered fit object with outliers omited
registered.final = lm(log(registered + 1) ~ ., data = data[!(rownames(data) %in% 
    c("6143", "378", "396")), c(-1, -10, -14)])

The fit for casual does not seem like it violates many assumptions for a linear regression. The Normal Q-Q plot shows that the model follows the normal curve relatively well, but there is slight deviation from at the tails. In general, the residuals follow the homoscedasticity assumption well, however, we see that the left side of the plot is obviously not homoscedastic since the residuals vs fitted plot shows points following a linear trend and the scale-location plot shows points following a check trend; this seems to be due to some characteristic of the data that I wasn’t able to identify absolutely. Besides this problem with the homoscedacity, there might also be a problem with the secondary cluster of points in the residuals vs leverage. These points seem to indicate that there is a particular group in the model that are being weighted relatively higher than the rest of the points (even though it is just ~.004 leverage).

In the fit for registered, it seems to follow the same violations as the casual variable, however, it seems to violate homoscedasticity to a lesser extent; we do not see a check pattern in the scale-location plot and points in both the scale-location and residuals vs fitted plots are spread out more evenly. We see also see some linear subtrends in the residuals vs fitted and in the scalelocation, but they are not that prominent. The normal Q-Q plot is very similar to the casual regression’s plot, however, we see the right tail of the plot following closer to the normal curve and the left tail of the plot following further from the normal curve. The residuals vs leverage plot also shows a secondary grouping of points with relatively more leverage.
